      <h1>New Kindles in Late 2026: Buy Now or Wait for EPUB Readers?</h1>
      <p class="meta"><time datetime="2026-07-19">Published July 19, 2026</time></p>

      <p>Amazon is preparing its biggest Kindle hardware refresh in years. Multiple sources — including Good e-Reader, Tech Times, and MakeUseOf — report that Amazon will release several new Kindle models in late 2026, driven primarily by the European Union's Battery Law that takes effect February 2027. This refresh affects every model in the lineup: the entry-level Kindle, Kindle Paperwhite, Paperwhite Signature Edition, Kindle Colorsoft Signature Edition, and possibly the long-rumored Kindle Oasis replacement.</p>

      <p>For EPUB readers, this raises a practical question: should you buy a current Kindle at a discount, or wait for the next generation? The answer depends on how you read EPUBs, whether you prioritize repairability, and what features matter most to you.</p>

      <h2>Why Amazon Is Refreshing the Entire Lineup</h2>

      <p>The primary driver is the EU Battery Law, which requires all e-readers, smartphones, and tablets sold in the European Union to have user-replaceable batteries starting February 18, 2027. Amazon's current Kindles use glued-sealed batteries — a design that makes devices thinner and water-resistant but effectively unrepairable when the battery degrades after three to five years.</p>

      <p>To continue selling in the EU — a market the company cannot afford to abandon, given the global Kindle market is projected to grow from USD 18.88 billion in 2026 to USD 24.99 billion by 2035 — Amazon must redesign every model with a snap-and-screw chassis that allows battery replacement with basic tools. Evidence of this effort appeared in the pulled Kindle firmware 5.19.4, which contained battery replacement workflow strings, QR-code-based parts ordering, and step-by-step repair instructions.</p>

      <p>A secondary driver is competition. Rakuten Kobo has been gaining momentum with native EPUB support, iFixit battery replacement partnerships, and its StoryGraph social reading integration. PocketBook offers open Linux-based devices with replaceable batteries already. Amazon needs to match both the repairability narrative and the reading experience to retain customers who value device longevity.</p>

