      <p>The processors are expected to be faster with more RAM — likely 1 GB or more — to support AI-powered features. Amazon has been investing heavily in AI for Kindle: AI-generated book summaries, AI-powered translation, and adaptive front-light based on reading patterns have all appeared in recent firmware updates. The new hardware needs the headroom to run these features smoothly.</p>

      <h2>What This Means for EPUB Readers</h2>

      <p>For EPUB readers, the new Kindles bring three concrete benefits:</p>

      <h3>1. Longer Device Lifespan</h3>

      <p>The most significant change is user-replaceable batteries. Current Kindles are designed with a sealed battery that is nearly impossible for the average user to replace. When the battery capacity drops below useful levels — typically after 1,000 to 1,500 charge cycles, or roughly three to five years of daily use — the device becomes a paperweight. A replacement Kindle costs $100 to $280 depending on the model.</p>

      <p>With a replaceable battery, you swap in a new cell for an estimated $20 to $50 and your Kindle runs for another three to five years. For EPUB readers who accumulate large libraries and prefer to keep the same device for years, this is transformative. Your EPUB files transferred via <a href="/blog/send-epub-to-kindle/">Send to Kindle</a> or <a href="/blog/calibre-epub-to-kindle-workflow-2026/">Calibre</a> will remain on a device you can keep for a decade or more.</p>

      <h3>2. EPUB Compatibility Improvements</h3>

      <p>Amazon has been gradually improving EPUB compatibility. In late 2025, Amazon began allowing KDP publishers to upload EPUB files directly. In June 2026, the company started showing DRM-free indicators on Kindle product pages. The new hardware is expected to handle EPUB files more gracefully, with better reflow support for complex EPUB layouts — including tables, footnotes, and embedded fonts — that current Kindles sometimes mangle during the AZW-to-EPUB conversion pipeline.</p>

      <p>While Kindle still does not offer native EPUB reading (it converts EPUB to AZW on the backend), the conversion pipeline improves with each firmware generation. The faster processor in the new models should make this conversion process nearly imperceptible.</p>

      <h3>3. Better Side-Loading Support</h3>

      <p>The leaked firmware 5.19.4 also hinted at improvements to the side-loading workflow — the process of transferring EPUB files from your computer to your Kindle via USB or the Send to Kindle app. Better USB transfer speeds, improved metadata parsing for cover images, and more reliable series sorting are all expected. For EPUB readers who manage their libraries with Calibre, these improvements directly affect the daily reading experience.</p>

      <h2>Buy Now: Who Should Grab a Current Kindle</h2>

      <p>Current-generation Kindles (the 12th-generation models released in 2024) are excellent devices, and with the refresh approaching, retailers are likely to offer significant discounts. Here is when it makes sense to buy now:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>You are on a budget.</strong> Discounted 2024 models could be $30 to $60 cheaper than the new ones. If price is the deciding factor, the current Paperwhite at a sale price is still a great EPUB reader, especially when paired with Calibre for library management.</li>
        <li><strong>You do not plan to keep the device for more than three years.</strong> If you upgrade regularly or tend to sell your old Kindle when a new model launches, the replaceable battery offers no practical benefit.</li>
        <li><strong>You use a Kindle primarily in the Amazon ecosystem.</strong> If you buy most of your books from Amazon and rarely side-load EPUBs, the current models handle that workflow perfectly well.</li>
        <li><strong>You need a device immediately.</strong> If your current e-reader just died or you need a replacement before the end of 2026, waiting is not practical. Any current Kindle will serve you well for years.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Wait for the New Models: Who Should Hold Off</h2>

      <p>On the other hand, several types of readers have strong reasons to wait:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>You keep devices for five years or more.</strong> If you are still using a Kindle from 2019 or earlier, you are exactly the type of reader the new models serve. A replaceable battery means you might keep the 2026 model through 2032 or beyond. For EPUB readers with large libraries who value continuity, the new models are worth the wait.</li>
        <li><strong>You side-load EPUBs regularly.</strong> If you use Calibre to manage your EPUB library and transfer books to your Kindle, the improved side-loading support and conversion pipeline will directly improve your workflow.</li>
        <li><strong>You want color or a premium form factor.</strong> If the Kindle Colorsoft's color E Ink display appeals to you for reading comics, graphic novels, or technical diagrams in EPUB format, the second-generation model will likely address the contrast and resolution limitations of the current generation.</li>
        <li><strong>You care about repairability and e-waste.</strong> If you prefer to buy devices that last and can be repaired rather than replaced, the new Kindles with user-replaceable batteries align with your values. The EU Battery Law represents a genuine shift toward sustainability in consumer electronics.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What About the Alternatives?</h2>

      <p>While waiting for the new Kindles, it is worth considering the alternatives, especially if you read EPUBs as your primary format:</p>

      <p><strong>Kobo.</strong> Kobo devices already have native EPUB support, user-replaceable batteries with iFixit parts availability, and the StoryGraph reading tracker integration. The Kobo Libra Colour and Clara Colour offer the best EPUB reading experience on dedicated hardware today. If you value EPUB compatibility above all, a Kobo is arguably better than even the next-generation Kindle.</p>

      <p><strong>PocketBook.</strong> PocketBook devices are open, running Linux with replaceable batteries and full EPUB support including Adobe DRM. The PocketBook Era Lite, released in early 2026, offers a 7-inch E Ink Carta 1300 display, IPX8 water resistance, and physical page-turn buttons at a competitive price point.</p>

      <p><strong>The wait-and-see approach.</strong> If your current device is still functional, the best strategy may be to wait. By early 2027, you will have the full picture: the new Kindle lineup will be available for hands-on reviews, Kobo will likely have refreshed its own lineup in response, and the EU Battery Law will be in effect. At that point, you can make a fully informed decision based on real hardware, not speculation.</p>

