      <h2>How to Prepare Your EPUB Library</h2>

      <p>Regardless of whether you buy a current Kindle on discount or wait for the new models, the most important step is to keep your EPUB library portable. Here is a simple checklist:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Convert any remaining non-EPUB files</strong> to EPUB using <a href="/">converter-epub.com</a>. This includes old MOBI files, PDFs, DOCX documents, and AZW3 books. The EPUB format is the universal standard and works on any e-reader.</li>
        <li><strong>Organize your library with Calibre.</strong> <a href="/blog/calibre-library-management-guide-2026/">Calibre's library management features</a> — metadata editing, series tagging, custom columns, and content server — make it easy to keep your EPUB collection portable and well-organized across devices.</li>
        <li><strong>Verify your EPUB files are valid.</strong> Use epubcheck or Calibre's built-in validation to confirm your EPUBs will render correctly on any device, including the new Kindles with their updated conversion pipeline.</li>
        <li><strong>Back up your library.</strong> A Calibre library is just a folder of EPUB files. Copy it to an external drive, cloud storage, or your own <a href="/blog/calibre-content-server-self-host-2026/">Calibre Content Server</a> for remote access.</li>
        <li><strong>Remove DRM where legally permitted.</strong> DRM-locked EPUBs purchased from one store may not transfer to another device. Keeping a DRM-free EPUB library ensures your books remain readable regardless of which e-reader brand you ultimately choose.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Our Take</h2>

      <p>The 2026 Kindle refresh is the most significant hardware change Amazon has made to its e-reader lineup since the original Kindle launched in 2007. User-replaceable batteries alone represent a philosophical shift from planned obsolescence to device longevity. Combined with faster processors, more RAM, and improved EPUB handling, the new Kindles will be genuinely better devices for EPUB readers.</p>

      <p>That said, the current generation Kindles are still excellent. If you find a deep discount, a 12th-gen Paperwhite paired with <a href="/blog/calibre-epub-to-kindle-workflow-2026/">Calibre for EPUB management</a> will serve you well for years. The new models are an improvement, not a revolution — unless you care deeply about repairability and keeping the same device for a decade.</p>

      <p>For most EPUB readers, the smartest move is to wait for the October 2026 announcements, compare the new models against the current discounted prices, and make a decision when both options are on the table. Your EPUB library will work on either choice.</p>

